Let $P(n)$ be the property: "For any $a_{1}, a_{2} \ldots a_{n}$, there exist natural numbers $b_{1}, \ldots b_{n}$ such that $a_{1} * b_{1}+a_{2} * b_{2}+\ldots .+a_{n} * b_{n}=d^{\prime \prime}$. Initialization: This is Bézout's theorem. Heredity: Let $n \geqslant 2 \in \mathbb{N}$. We assume the property is true at rank $n$. We are given $\left\{a_{1}, a_{1} \ldots a_{n}, a_{n+1}\right\}$ natural numbers. Let $d_{n}$ be the GCD of $\left\{a_{1}, a_{1} \ldots a_{n}, a_{n}\right\}$. Note that the GCD of $\left\{a_{1}, a_{1} \ldots a_{n}, a_{n+1}\right\}$ is equal to the GCD of $d_{n}$ and $a_{n+1}$ (detailed proof in progress). According to Bézout's theorem, denoting $d_{n+1}$ as the GCD of $\left\{a_{1}, a_{1} \ldots a_{n}, a_{n+1}\right\}$, there exist natural numbers $u$ and $v$ such that $d_{n} * u + a_{n+1} * v = d_{n+1}$. By the induction hypothesis, we have $c_{1}, \ldots c_{n}$ such that $a_{1} * c_{1} + a_{2} * c_{2} + \ldots .+ a_{n} * c_{n} = d_{n}$, hence

$$
\begin{aligned}
& \left(a_{1} * c_{1} + a_{2} * c_{2} + \ldots .+ a_{n} * c_{n}\right) * u + a_{n+1} * v = d_{n+1} \\
& a_{1} * c_{1} * u + a_{2} * c_{2} * u + \ldots .+ a_{n} * c_{n} * u + a_{n+1} * v = d_{n+1}
\end{aligned}
$$

By setting, for all indices $i$ different from $n+1: b_{i} = c_{i} * u$ and $b_{n+1} = v$, we have shown that $P(n+1)$ is satisfied. By the principle of induction, the property is true for any $n$.

Note that $b_{i}$ is not necessarily equal to $c_{i}$, which is why it is useful to use different letters in the induction hypothesis to avoid any confusion.

