It is $x^{2}-a^{2} y^{2}=(x+a y)(x-a y)=b$. The number $b$ is thus the product of two factors $f_{1}$ and $f_{2}$. If $b$ is a prime number, then one of the factors is 1, the other is $b$. If $b$ is not a prime number, then $b$ can be decomposed into a product of two factors in only finitely many ways (this follows from the fact that the prime factorization of $b$ is unique and contains only finitely many factors).

For each possible decomposition of $b$ into two factors, the following two systems of equations thus arise:

$$
\begin{array}{ll}
x+a y=f_{1} & x-a y=f_{2} \\
x+a y=f_{2} & x-a y=f_{1}
\end{array}
$$

The solutions are

$$
\begin{array}{ll}
x=\frac{f_{1}+f_{2}}{2 a} & y=\frac{f_{1}-f_{2}}{2 a} \\
x=\frac{f_{1}+f_{2}}{2 a} & y=\frac{f_{2}-f_{1}}{2 a}
\end{array}
$$

They are integers precisely when $2 a$ is a divisor of $\left|f_{1}-f_{2}\right|$. Since each factorization provides at most two solutions and the number of factorizations is finite, the number of (integer) solutions can also be at most finite.

